{"title":"Session 19: Brownian Motion ôñ ItûÇ ôñ OU (Concepts Only)","markdown":{"headingText":"Session 19: Brownian Motion ôñ ItûÇ ôñ OU (Concepts Only)","headingAttr":{"id":"sec-session-19","classes":[],"keyvalue":[]},"containsRefs":false,"markdown":"\n| | |\n|---|---|\n| **Unit** | 4 ã Math Intuition Bridges |\n| **Book Chapters** | 10, 12 (concepts only ã full derivations in Session 25 Track 2) |\n| **Track** | Common core (both tracks) |\n\n::: callout-important\n## Reading Notes for Unit 4 (Sessions 19ã24)\n\nThis unit teaches the **conceptual content of Part 2 of the book** ã what the math *means*, what it *does*, and *why* it works ã without proofs or detailed derivations. The goal is for **all students** to leave Unit 4 with a working intuition about the GE-LAV machinery.\n\n**Track 1 students** are assessed only on conceptual understanding. PS3 includes intuition-level questions for Track 1.\n\n**Track 2 students** will revisit each topic in Sessions 25ã29 with full mathematical rigor ã proofs, derivations, numerical implementations. PS3 for Track 2 includes mathematical work.\n\nIf you find Unit 4 too easy, you'll love Sessions 25ã29. If you find it too hard, the framework's *applications* (Unit 3 and Session 25+ Track 1) don't require this level of detail.\n:::\n\n## Learning Objectives\n\nBy the end of this session, students will be able to:\n\n1. **Explain Brownian motion in plain language** ã what it is, why it's the canonical model of randomness in continuous time.\n2. **State the four key properties** of Brownian motion (continuity, independent increments, normal distribution of increments, scale).\n3. **State ItûÇ's lemma conceptually** ã the \"chain rule\" of stochastic calculus ã and why it has an extra term compared to ordinary calculus.\n4. **Re-derive (informally) the OU process** as a special case of an ItûÇ SDE with mean-reverting drift.\n5. **Recognize** when ItûÇ calculus is the right tool (continuous random processes) and when it isn't (jumps, discrete states).\n\n## Pre-Class Assignment\n\n- **Read:** Book Chapter 10 sections relevant to Brownian motion and ItûÇ calculus ã read for *concepts*, not formulas. Skim the technical derivations.\n- **Watch:** Pre-class video (10 min) explaining Brownian motion intuitively (link on course site)\n\n## In-Class Outline (75 minutes)\n\n| Time | Segment | Format |\n|---|---|---|\n| 0:00ã0:10 | Why we need this ôñ Math intuition bridges begin | Lecture |\n| 0:10ã0:30 | Brownian motion: the canonical continuous random process | Lecture + simulation |\n| 0:30ã0:50 | ItûÇ's lemma: chain rule with a twist | Lecture + visual |\n| 0:50ã1:05 | OU as an ItûÇ SDE | Lecture |\n| 1:05ã1:15 | What ItûÇ calculus can and can't do | Discussion |\n\n## Discussion Questions\n\n1. The ItûÇ correction term $\\frac{1}{2} f''(X_t) \\sigma^2 dt$ has the same mathematical form as the Jensen convexity correction $\\frac{1}{2} f''(X) \\text{Var}(X)$. Why are these two expressions the same? What's the deep connection?\n2. The OU process has $\\kappa = 0.45$/yr, implying half-life of liquidity shocks ~18 months. Many practitioners would estimate half-life closer to 6-12 months (faster mean reversion). What evidence would resolve this?\n3. Real liquidity has jumps (March 2020). The GE-LAV core uses pure ItûÇ (no jumps). For the purposes of valuation, is this approximation acceptable? When does it break?\n\n## Worked Example: Applying ItûÇ's Lemma\n\n**Setup:** Let $L_t$ follow OU with $\\kappa = 0.45$, $\\sigma_L = 0.32$, $\\bar{L} = 1.0$. Compute the expected value and variance of $f(L_t) = L_t^2$ at $t = 5$, given $L_0 = 0$.\n\n**Step 1: Apply ItûÇ's lemma to $f(L) = L^2$**\n\n$f'(L) = 2L$, $f''(L) = 2$\n\n$df(L_t) = 2L_t dL_t + \\frac{1}{2}(2)\\sigma_L^2 dt = 2L_t [\\kappa(\\bar{L} - L_t)dt + \\sigma_L dW_t] + \\sigma_L^2 dt$\n\nTake expectations (Brownian term vanishes in expectation):\n$\\frac{d}{dt} E[L_t^2] = 2\\kappa \\bar{L} E[L_t] - 2\\kappa E[L_t^2] + \\sigma_L^2$\n\n**Step 2: We need $E[L_t]$ first**\n\n$E[L_t | L_0 = 0] = \\bar{L}(1 - e^{-\\kappa t}) = 1.0 \\cdot (1 - e^{-2.25}) = 1.0 \\cdot 0.894 = 0.894$\n\nSo at $t = 5$, $E[L_5] = 0.894$ (close to long-run mean).\n\n**Step 3: Variance**\n\n$\\text{Var}[L_t | L_0] = \\frac{\\sigma_L^2}{2\\kappa}(1 - e^{-2\\kappa t}) = \\frac{0.1024}{0.9}(1 - e^{-4.5}) = 0.1138 \\cdot 0.989 = 0.1126$\n\n**Step 4: $E[L_t^2]$**\n\n$E[L_t^2] = \\text{Var}[L_t] + (E[L_t])^2 = 0.1126 + 0.894^2 = 0.1126 + 0.799 = 0.912$\n\n**Interpretation:** Starting at $L_0 = 0$ (stressed but not crisis), 5 years later we expect $E[L] \\approx 0.89$ (close to long-run mean) with variance $\\approx 0.11$ (close to stationary). The $E[L^2]$ value $\\approx 0.91$ matters for the *quadratic* premium function $\\pi(L)$.\n\n## What to Expect Next Session\n\nSession 20 introduces **stochastic control and the HJB equation**. We'll cover:\n\n- The optimal control problem: choose actions $u_t$ to maximize expected utility\n- The dynamic programming principle (Bellman's logic)\n- The HJB equation: a PDE that the value function must satisfy\n- Application: the LP's exit timing problem (Session 11ã13 revisited mathematically)\n\n**Reading:** Book Chapter 11 (concepts only ã skim the proofs).\n\n**For Track 2:** Session 25 derives the HJB for the GE-LAV exit problem with full smooth pasting and verification theorems. Today is the conceptual setup.\n\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\n[ã Session 18](session-18.qmd) | [Schedule](../schedule.qmd) | [Next: Session 20 ã](session-20.qmd)\n","srcMarkdownNoYaml":""},"formats":{"html":{"identifier":{"display-name":"HTML","target-format":"html","base-format":"html"},"execute":{"fig-width":7,"fig-height":5,"fig-format":"retina","fig-dpi":96,"df-print":"default","error":false,"eval":true,"cache":null,"freeze":"auto","echo":true,"output":true,"warning":false,"include":true,"keep-md":false,"keep-ipynb":false,"ipynb":n